  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a traditional DCF inherently misses — and why evaluating a REIT requires looking beyond standard cash flow analysis.</p>

  <h3>Why REITs often look "Overvalued" in a DCF</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>High Debt Loads:</strong> REITs intentionally carry massive amounts of debt to finance property acquisitions. A traditional DCF subtracts all net debt from Enterprise Value to find Equity Value. This penalizes the company for its core business model.</li>
    <li><strong>Depreciation:</strong> Real estate depreciates on paper (reducing net income) but often appreciates in reality. This creates a divergence between GAAP earnings/cash flow and the actual net asset value (NAV) of the properties.</li>
    <li><strong>Funds From Operations (FFO):</strong> The market typically values REITs on a multiple of FFO or Adjusted FFO (AFFO), not Unlevered Free Cash Flow. FFO adds back depreciation and amortization, providing a much higher base number for valuation.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Upside risks to Welltower</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Demographic Tailwinds:</strong> The "Silver Tsunami" of aging baby boomers guarantees an expanding addressable market for senior housing over the next two decades.</li>
    <li><strong>Pricing Power:</strong> Welltower has demonstrated strong pricing power, passing on inflation costs to residents through significant rent increases in recent years.</li>
    <li><strong>Interest Rate Cuts:</strong> Any significant drop in interest rates would drastically lower their cost of capital, making debt financing cheaper and boosting bottom-line metrics.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Labor Shortages:</strong> The healthcare sector faces acute staffing shortages. Rising wage pressures for nurses and care staff can compress operating margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Overbuilding:</strong> If developers flood the market with new senior housing supply, occupancy rates and pricing power could decline.</li>
    <li><strong>Higher-for-Longer Rates:</strong> If interest rates stay elevated, refinancing their massive $21.3B debt load will eat into distributable cash flows.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why does the intrinsic value look so low compared to the share price?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Standard DCF models heavily penalize companies with massive debt loads. Welltower holds $21.38 billion in debt to finance its properties. When we subtract this from the Enterprise Value, it crushes the per-share Equity Value. In reality, the market values REITs based on Funds From Operations (FFO) and the underlying value of their real estate, not an unlevered DCF.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why use an 8.5% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">A discount rate reflects the required return for the risk taken. While standard equities might demand 10%+, REITs often have highly predictable, contractually obligated rent revenues, making their cash flows safer. 8.5% offers a balanced required return above the current 10-year Treasury yield.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>What is Funds From Operations (FFO) and why does it matter?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">FFO adds depreciation and amortization back to net income. Because real estate tends to hold its value or appreciate (unlike factory machinery that actually breaks down), subtracting depreciation makes a REIT look less profitable than it is. FFO is the standardized metric the industry uses to measure a REIT's operating performance.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value using a traditional DCF method. For REITs like Welltower, you should also consider NAV (Net Asset Value) and Price/FFO multiples. This tool is meant to provide transparency into one specific valuation method.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How often is this updated?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">We update this analysis when Welltower reports quarterly earnings or when material events change the underlying thesis.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

